Interview Questions
What is Browser Storage?
Browser Storage refers to mechanisms that allow browsers to store data locally, including Cookies, Local Storage, and Session Storage.

What is the difference between Cookies and Local Storage?
Cookies are automatically sent with HTTP requests and are commonly used for authentication.

Local Storage is only accessible through JavaScript and is not automatically sent to the server.

What is Session Storage?
Session Storage stores data only for the lifetime of a browser tab and is deleted when the tab is closed.

Why is storing JWTs in Local Storage risky?
Because JavaScript can access Local Storage, an XSS vulnerability may allow attackers to steal JWTs.

What does HttpOnly do?
HttpOnly prevents JavaScript from reading cookies, helping protect against cookie theft through XSS.

Can XSS steal an HttpOnly cookie?
No.

JavaScript cannot directly read an HttpOnly cookie.

However, XSS may still perform actions as the authenticated user because the browser automatically includes the cookie in requests.

